<font color="#FF0000">WE'RE ALL SO VERY PROUD OF YOU</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov 16 22:49:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Dr. Spatz<br>
I recently spoke at a school on Veteran's Day. The principal spoke with me after the assembly. He said that a few of the students were absent that day because their religion and their parents would not allow them to celebrate or attend Veteran's Day activities. This &quot;disgusted&quot; him. He was sure that I felt the sameway. My answer to him also applies to you and your posts. I told him as I am telling you that it doesn&quot;t anger me,quite the opposite.It proves that the system and our form of government is working.<br>
Freedom of speech and freedom of religion is the entitlement of every American citizen. And a veteran gave those freedoms and privleges among others to us free of charge. It cost them plenty. From the American Revoultion to Desert Storm men have and will continue to go to war to defend those rights. I hope you don't think that's being &quot;corny&quot;.  Because in some of your posts you have alluded that it is. That would be offensive and rude.<br>
Of course Vietnam was wrong.I don't think you will find anybody,espically a vet, to disagree with you.You protested the war,I fought it.You chose a path to follow like so many of our generation did. I have no animosity or anger toward anyone who chose flight over fight.It was their right as it was mine to hold my right hand up and say &quot;I will&quot;.<br>
I was a Army Medic for 14 months in Vietnam stationed at a firebase (Mace) with the 199th light infantry and the 46th Engineers. Myself and another medic Charles Zinn(a C.O. for religious reasons) had many late night chats about C.O.s.  Zinn never carried a weapon in Vietnam-ever. You want to talk about commitment to your beliefs? You want to honor the resistor? We could take a few pointers from men like Zinn. Walking around the jungles of Vietnam without a weapon was, I thought insane at best. But Zinn is alive and well this very day.<br>
All Army medics back then were trained at Ft Sam Houston in San Antonio,Tx. All CO's religious,political or otherwise were there too. We were separated in the barracks, CO's on the bottom floor and the rest of us,enlistees and draftees were on the top. Which brings me to you.<br>
I am not trying to doubt your bedpan service during the war,but where did you serve? Civillian or military hospitals? Because it was my belief from talking to COs that you had the options of jail time or becoming a medic. Enlighten me. Because if your bedpan service was part of a medical school deferment toward your M.D. degree,then my friend that&quot;s a bedpan of a different color. No disrespect intended.      <br>
From one of your earlier posts you queried &quot;Where's our memorial&quot;?  I believe it&quot;s in Ohio. Called Kent State. Crosby,Stills and Nash wrote a song about it. Kind of crazy isn' it. You protested the war, I fought it.  Your people died because they were at the wrong place at the wrong time and so did mine. <br>
Regards,<br><br>
&quot;Bacsi&quot; (Vietnameese for Doctor-add it to your new vocabulary)<br>
 
